# Rule 3 — Dependency rules

**Very important.** Cursor must **never** violate this order.  
A package may depend only on packages **above** it (upstream). It must **never** depend on packages **below** it (downstream).

## Canonical order (never invert)

```text
Core
  ↓
Support
  ↓
Validation
  ↓
Security
  ↓
Database
  ↓
Fields
  ↓
Rest (framework HTTP)
  ↓
API (application routes)
  ↓
Admin
  ↓
Builder
```

Read top → bottom as **implementation / dependency direction**: lower packages may use upper ones; upper packages must not import lower ones.

Examples:

- ✅ `Fields` may use `Database`, `Validation`, `Security`, `Support`, `Core`
- ✅ `Rest` may use `Fields` (+ upstream); must not use `Admin` / `Builder` / `Wordpress`
- ✅ `API` may use `Rest` / `Fields` (+ upstream)
- ✅ `Admin` may use `API` contracts only if SPEC allows — prefer Fields/Security/UI; never own field engine
- ❌ `Core` must not import `Support`, `Fields`, `API`, …
- ❌ `Database` must not import `Fields` or `API`
- ❌ `Fields` must not import `API`, `Admin`, or `Builder`
- ❌ `API` must not import `Admin` or `Builder`
- ❌ `Admin` must not import `Builder` internals
- ❌ `Builder` must not redefine Fields / Validation / Database engines

## UI & Wordpress (same rule)

In this monorepo they fit **without** breaking the chain:

```text
… → Fields → API
              ↘
               UI → Admin → Builder
                            ↘
                             Wordpress (glue; mounts others; no domain engines)
```

- `UI` is above `Admin` (Admin may use UI; UI must not use Admin/Builder/Fields storage).
- `Wordpress` is outermost glue — bridges only; never invert (don’t put field logic in wordpress that Core should own).

Detail map: `.cursor/context/project.md` · each package SPEC **Dependency Rules**.

## Hard bans (summary)

| Package | Must not depend on |
| ------- | ------------------ |
| `core` | Any other OpenMeta package |
| `support` | validation, security, database, fields, api, ui, admin, builder, wordpress |
| `validation` | security*, database, fields, api, ui, admin, builder, wordpress |
| `security` | database, fields, api, ui, admin, builder, wordpress |
| `database` | fields, api, ui, admin, builder, wordpress |
| `fields` | rest, api, ui, admin, builder, wordpress |
| `rest` | api, ui, admin, builder, wordpress |
| `api` | ui, admin, builder, wordpress |
| `ui` | admin, builder, fields storage, api, wordpress |
| `admin` | builder, wordpress internals, raw `$wpdb` |
| `builder` | wordpress internals; field-type engine; GraphQL server |
| `wordpress` | reimplementing fields/validation/database — bridges only |

\* Prefer Validation not depending on Security; Security may use Support/Core only.

## Practice

1. Before any `use OpenMeta\...` across packages → check this order.
2. New dependency edge → **update SPEC first**, then code.
3. Depend on **public contracts / façades**, not another package’s private internals.
4. If a “convenient” import would point **uphill** on the diagram → **stop**. Redesign or ask.

**Violating this graph = broken architecture.** Do not ship it.
